# isopod runtime tiers — how `isopod doctor` classifies the configured runtime
# (the hardening.conf `runtime` directive / ISOPOD_RUNTIME) and whether
# `isopod create` sizes a default --memory for it.
#
#   tier 2  syscall sandbox, shared host kernel, no /dev/kvm needed (e.g. gVisor)
#   tier 3  microVM, separate guest kernel, needs /dev/kvm (e.g. Kata, krun)
#
# Columns: <runtime-name> <tier>. The name matches what you pass to --runtime
# (and to the `runtime` directive / ISOPOD_RUNTIME). Unlisted runtimes still
# work; doctor just cannot name their tier and create skips the memory default.
runsc         2
runsc-kvm     2
kata          3
kata-runtime  3
kata-qemu     3
kata-fc       3
kata-clh      3
krun          3
crun-vm       3
